baseline: Frequency of discomfort symptoms was unrelated to the variables of the medical examinations, but positively related to measures of anxiety, and negatively related to satisfaction with the situation at home and (at some age levels) to self-esteem and to experienced attractiveness and body-image satisfaction.
high_intensity: Frequency of discomfort symptoms was unrelated to the variables of the extreme medical examinations, but positively related to measures of intense anxiety, and negatively related to satisfaction with the situation at home and (at some age levels) to low self-esteem and to poor experienced attractiveness and body-image satisfaction.
low_intensity: Frequency of mild discomfort symptoms was unrelated to the variables of the medical examinations, but positively related to minor anxiety, and somewhat negatively related to satisfaction with the situation at home and (at some age levels) to slightly reduced self-esteem and to experienced attractiveness and body-image satisfaction.

baseline: Analysis of data support the notion that the fainting episodes represent a form of transitory anxiety attacks in response to environmental stress and are not related either to hysteria or to anxiety state.
high_intensity: Analysis of data support the notion that the fainting episodes represent a form of transitory anxiety attacks in response to extreme environmental stress and are not related either to hysteria or to anxiety state.
low_intensity: Analysis of data support the notion that the fainting episodes represent a form of minor anxiety attacks in response to environmental stress and are not related either to hysteria or to anxiety state.

baseline: There is mental retardation secondary to language deficits, but no social withdrawal, overwhelming anxiety, or obsessive need for sameness.
high_intensity: There is mental retardation secondary to significant language deficits, but no social withdrawal, intense anxiety, or obsessive need for sameness.
low_intensity: There is mental retardation secondary to minor language deficits, but no social withdrawal, mild anxiety, or obsessive need for sameness.

baseline: Previous research has validated finger pulse volume (FPV) as a measure of anxiety in response to threat of physical harm.
high_intensity: Previous research has validated finger pulse volume (FPV) as a measure of panic in response to threat of severe physical abuse.
low_intensity: Previous research has validated finger pulse volume (FPV) as a measure of unease in response to threat of mild physical abuse.
